WEBVTT

00:18.185 --> 00:19.769
<i>MAN ON RADIO: The family
of a woman who died</i>

00:19.853 --> 00:21.187
<i>after a botched police raid</i>

00:21.271 --> 00:24.148
<i>intends to sue the city for $500 million,</i>

00:24.233 --> 00:26.401
<i>naming the city, the police department,</i>

00:26.527 --> 00:28.611
<i>and the officers involved in the raid.</i>

00:28.696 --> 00:32.615
<i>You're listening to WNYC
and wnyc.org.</i>

00:32.741 --> 00:34.367
<i>It's 50 degrees right now.</i>

00:34.451 --> 00:37.870
<i>We have cloudy skies
over the city at 4:29.</i>

00:37.996 --> 00:39.455
<i>Good morning...</i>

00:47.589 --> 00:49.340
(ALARM BEEPING)

00:51.552 --> 00:52.969
(BEEPING STOPS)

00:53.053 --> 00:54.887
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

01:00.894 --> 01:02.311
(GRUNTING)

01:06.316 --> 01:07.316
Oh... (COUGHS)

01:07.401 --> 01:08.443
(SNORTS)

01:09.987 --> 01:12.405
Remember to reset the clock.

01:12.489 --> 01:13.865
Yeah.

01:26.670 --> 01:28.337
-Thank you.
-Look at this.

01:28.839 --> 01:31.007
Almost 8% up from last year.

01:32.009 --> 01:34.385
Yeah, but that's a nationwide trend now.

01:36.472 --> 01:38.598
What are you thinking? More cutbacks?

01:38.682 --> 01:40.141
I'm not sure.

01:40.225 --> 01:42.935
We'll know more after this afternoon.

01:44.730 --> 01:45.938
(SIGHS) Oh, by the way,

01:46.023 --> 01:48.024
I caught the last 10 minutes
of your husband's, uh,

01:48.108 --> 01:49.442
documentary the other night.

01:49.526 --> 01:51.527
Really interesting stuff.

01:51.612 --> 01:53.905
I'll let him know. He'll be pleased.

01:53.989 --> 01:56.032
It's a real labor of love for him.

01:56.116 --> 01:59.035
He was, what, the, uh, director?

01:59.119 --> 02:00.703
Yeah, director.

02:01.288 --> 02:02.789
Producer.

02:02.873 --> 02:04.791
Writer, voice-over. (CHUCKLES)

02:05.334 --> 02:06.918
It's real low-budget stuff.

02:07.044 --> 02:08.377
It's tough
to make a living in that business.

02:12.966 --> 02:14.550
(SNORTS)

02:17.221 --> 02:18.429
Oh, shit.

02:18.514 --> 02:19.597
Kids!

02:19.681 --> 02:21.557
Up! Up! Up! Up!

02:21.725 --> 02:25.394
We're late. Your mom forgot
to reset the alarm again!

02:32.236 --> 02:34.070
Dad, these shoes hurt.

02:34.154 --> 02:35.571
Well, then change them.

02:36.990 --> 02:38.241
Kristen!

02:39.910 --> 02:40.993
Pour yourjuice, Jesse.

02:41.078 --> 02:42.662
Just pour yourjuice.

02:42.746 --> 02:43.996
-(LIQUID SPILLS)
-Oh, shit!

02:44.373 --> 02:45.957
Uh, Dad, where's mom?

02:46.416 --> 02:49.001
She's in... Cincinnati or Chicago.

02:49.086 --> 02:50.127
Someplace like that.

02:52.089 --> 02:53.673
Oh, my God. It's late.

02:53.757 --> 02:55.508
I have to be at school early today!

02:55.592 --> 02:56.676
Well, that's not gonna happen.

02:56.760 --> 02:59.053
JESSE: Hey, uh, Dad, do they
have a Niketown in Milwaukee?

02:59.137 --> 03:00.513
-(SIGHS)
-Actually...

03:00.597 --> 03:03.015
Uh, I'm just gonna call mom.

03:03.100 --> 03:04.308
Hey, Jesse.

03:04.393 --> 03:06.185
-She is on an airplane, okay?
-I know that.

03:06.270 --> 03:07.603
I'm leaving her a message.

03:09.898 --> 03:13.401
Leah, I have to make
a very big decision by this evening,

03:13.485 --> 03:14.777
so let me ask you something.

03:17.030 --> 03:19.782
What would you say if...

03:20.909 --> 03:23.327
I offered you the V.P. slot?

03:26.456 --> 03:27.415
Wow. (CHUCKLES)

03:27.499 --> 03:28.499
(CHUCKLES)

03:32.546 --> 03:34.463
Do I have to say yes right now?

03:38.302 --> 03:39.927
When do we have to be back?

03:40.137 --> 03:41.888
We're booked on the 6:00 flight.

03:46.393 --> 03:48.144
Let's stay over.

03:50.314 --> 03:51.981
We'll discuss this over dinner.

03:56.028 --> 03:57.403
COOPER: Now, listen, tell
them I'm five minutes away.

03:57.487 --> 03:58.487
JESSE: Dad. Dad.

03:58.572 --> 04:00.406
I've got the presentation.
I'm ready to roll.

04:00.490 --> 04:02.241
-KRISTEN: Dad, we have to go.
-(HORN HONKING)

04:02.326 --> 04:03.534
Just around the corner.

04:03.660 --> 04:05.119
JESSE: Dad, I really need
some lunch money.

04:05.203 --> 04:06.412
Hey, all right, I've got it.

04:06.496 --> 04:07.830
(CELL PHONE RINGS)

04:07.915 --> 04:09.457
Cooper's office. Jesse speaking.

04:09.833 --> 04:10.833
-LEAH: Kiddo!
-Hey, Mom.

04:10.959 --> 04:12.251
<i>-Morning, honey.
-(HONKING CONTINUES)</i>

04:12.336 --> 04:13.377
These new shoes
are really hurting.

04:13.462 --> 04:14.629
KRISTEN: Talk to mom later.

04:14.713 --> 04:17.255
Okay, honey, we'll go this
weekend and get you some Vans.

04:17.341 --> 04:18.423
<i>That's what you said last week.</i>

04:19.426 --> 04:21.344
COOPER:
Jesse, we gotta go.

04:21.428 --> 04:23.054
-See you later. Bye.
-Good.

04:23.138 --> 04:24.263
All right, hang on.

04:24.348 --> 04:25.765
Bye, kids. Love you.

04:25.849 --> 04:27.725
Bye. Give me a hug. Let's go. All right.

04:27.809 --> 04:29.352
Hold your brother's hand going out.

04:30.145 --> 04:31.228
Have fun.

04:31.313 --> 04:32.521
(HONKING CONTINUES)

04:33.774 --> 04:36.025
Kristen, hold your brother's hand!

04:36.944 --> 04:38.611
Cooper, what are you doing?
It's almost 8:30.

04:38.695 --> 04:40.863
Well, we ran a little bit behind today.

04:41.031 --> 04:43.491
Someone forgot to reset the alarm.

04:43.575 --> 04:45.117
Jesse...

04:45.202 --> 04:46.786
-No, don't go over that way.
-Why not?

04:46.870 --> 04:48.537
-MAN: Hey, asshole!
-(HONKING CONTINUES)

04:50.374 --> 04:51.374
Jesse, stop! Jesse!

04:51.458 --> 04:53.000
-(TIRES SCREECH)
-(THUD)

04:53.085 --> 04:54.085
Oh, my God!

04:54.169 --> 04:55.252
Cooper?

04:55.337 --> 04:56.671
Oh, my God!

04:56.755 --> 04:58.047
Jesse!

04:58.173 --> 04:59.757
Jesse! Jesse!

05:00.425 --> 05:02.885
(INDISTINCT TALKING)

05:07.516 --> 05:09.225
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

05:23.198 --> 05:24.657
(SIGHS)

05:34.543 --> 05:35.793
(SIGHS)

05:39.548 --> 05:41.882
We've got to get out of the city.

05:53.895 --> 05:55.396
How are we gonna do that?

06:03.613 --> 06:05.364
LEAH: So, what about myjob?

06:05.449 --> 06:07.241
COOPER: Take a year off.

06:07.325 --> 06:09.869
<i>Write a book.
You always wanted to write a book.</i>

06:11.788 --> 06:14.665
<i>JESSE: So, Mom,
how can we afford something so big?</i>

06:14.750 --> 06:16.125
<i>LEAH:
Well, we would get a lot of money</i>

06:16.209 --> 06:18.044
<i>for our house in the city.</i>

06:18.128 --> 06:20.254
<i>Big houses in the country
cost a lot less</i>

06:20.338 --> 06:22.048
<i>than tiny houses in New York city.</i>

06:22.132 --> 06:23.257
<i>COOPER:
Plus, there are some houses</i>

06:23.341 --> 06:25.217
<i>that the bank has foreclosed on.</i>

06:25.302 --> 06:27.720
<i>That means someone ran out of money</i>

06:27.804 --> 06:30.264
<i>and so the bank can
sell it at a really cheap price.</i>

06:30.348 --> 06:31.432
<i>KRISTEN:
That's screwed up.</i>

06:31.516 --> 06:33.934
<i>LEAH:
Well, so is your attitude, young lady.</i>

06:34.061 --> 06:35.186
(BELL DINGS)

06:37.731 --> 06:38.898
MAN: I was reading
the articles.

06:38.982 --> 06:40.232
RUBY:
Sure you were.

06:40.317 --> 06:41.901
-I was!
-That's... (LAUGHS)

06:47.240 --> 06:50.951
Hi. Uh, could you
fill it up with unleaded regular, please?

06:51.453 --> 06:52.495
Sure.

06:58.168 --> 06:59.794
I'm gonna stretch.

07:01.296 --> 07:02.379
(GROANING)

07:04.049 --> 07:05.424
RUBY: Do you want me to check the oil?

07:05.509 --> 07:07.176
Oh, that's okay.

07:08.845 --> 07:09.887
Great weather.

07:11.098 --> 07:12.848
Yeah, nice.

07:15.310 --> 07:16.852
Uh, we're serving lunch.

07:16.937 --> 07:18.395
Do you want me to tell you the specials?

07:18.647 --> 07:20.523
Oh, that's all right. We already ate.

07:21.316 --> 07:22.733
-KRISTEN: Hey, Mom?
-LEAH: Huh?

07:22.818 --> 07:25.236
How many more of these
stupid houses do we have to see today?

07:25.320 --> 07:26.946
This should be the last one.

07:27.197 --> 07:28.989
I couldn't get it arranged to get inside,

07:29.074 --> 07:30.282
so we'll just take a quick look

07:30.367 --> 07:32.785
and then we'll be
on the way home, okay?

07:32.869 --> 07:34.120
Promise.

07:34.246 --> 07:35.871
Where you guys headed?

07:36.790 --> 07:38.332
Cold Creek Manor.

07:39.960 --> 07:41.627
So if we just go on down the road here,

07:41.711 --> 07:43.504
are we going the right direction?

07:43.588 --> 07:45.798
Yeah, it's about a mile that way.

07:45.882 --> 07:47.216
Thanks.

08:09.072 --> 08:10.322
COOPER: Look.

08:19.374 --> 08:20.416
-Huh.
-Wow.

08:20.500 --> 08:21.584
-Wow.
-Ooh.

08:24.254 --> 08:25.754
-(SIGHS)
-Wow.

08:26.423 --> 08:27.673
Hey, don't fool with that, okay?

08:27.757 --> 08:28.799
-Look.
-What?

08:28.884 --> 08:30.176
-It's unlocked.
-Hey.

08:31.094 --> 08:32.469
Here, hold this.

08:34.806 --> 08:35.931
JESSE:
It's unlocked.

08:36.015 --> 08:37.683
What are you doing?

08:37.767 --> 08:39.684
-Dad, we can see it from right here.
-Cooper...

08:39.811 --> 08:41.187
-What?
-We can see it right here.

08:41.270 --> 08:43.606
Come on, we'll just take a
look. Just take a little peek.

08:43.690 --> 08:44.732
Nobody here.

08:57.787 --> 08:58.787
Dad...

08:58.872 --> 09:00.456
LEAH: Kristen, you stay
close to your brother.

09:00.540 --> 09:01.999
COOPER:
Hey, stay together.

09:02.083 --> 09:03.459
JESSE: Catch me!

09:12.010 --> 09:14.136
(BIRDS CAWING)

09:18.308 --> 09:19.558
COOPER: Kids?

09:19.643 --> 09:21.936
-Once again, don't go far.
-Come on! Hey!

09:33.657 --> 09:34.782
(SIGHS)

09:59.349 --> 10:00.808
(HINGES CREAKING)

10:01.434 --> 10:03.352
LEAH: I mean, we are
about to break the law here.

10:03.436 --> 10:05.104
JESSE: Yeah, Dad.
Let's break the law.

10:05.188 --> 10:07.064
We're just gonna
look around for two seconds,

10:07.148 --> 10:08.941
and then we're outta here.

10:09.025 --> 10:10.818
(STAIRS CREAKING)

10:31.047 --> 10:32.631
(SIGHS)

10:41.391 --> 10:42.558
-(COUGHS)
-Oh, sorry.

10:42.642 --> 10:43.726
Thanks, Dad.

10:47.230 --> 10:48.230
LEAH: What are these?

10:50.317 --> 10:53.027
Those are farming things.

10:53.862 --> 10:55.529
For what?

10:55.613 --> 10:57.072
For farming.

10:57.699 --> 10:59.992
Uh, yeah. Dad, we got that.

11:01.619 --> 11:03.329
(FLOOR CREAKS)

11:15.759 --> 11:17.593
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

11:18.595 --> 11:19.928
(WINGS FLAPPING)

11:36.780 --> 11:39.323
(PIANO MUSIC PLAYS)

11:42.285 --> 11:44.411
Can we buy this house, please?

11:44.496 --> 11:45.579
It's so cool. Can we?

11:45.663 --> 11:46.914
I don't know. I don't know.

11:46.998 --> 11:48.082
What do you think, angel?

11:48.166 --> 11:49.750
It's pretty cool.

11:49.834 --> 11:51.043
Mom, what do you think?

11:51.127 --> 11:52.378
We'll see.

11:52.462 --> 11:53.504
(GASPS)

11:53.630 --> 11:54.713
(SCREAMS)

11:56.049 --> 11:58.008
We had no intention to break the law.

11:58.093 --> 11:59.385
No harm done.

11:59.469 --> 12:01.887
I didn't know the property
was on the market yet.

12:03.264 --> 12:04.598
Don't bother, young lady.

12:04.682 --> 12:07.059
Mobiles do not function in Bellingham.

12:08.144 --> 12:09.853
You folks gonna buy it?

12:09.938 --> 12:11.397
Uh, we'd like to. We're, uh...

12:11.481 --> 12:12.564
We're thinking about it.

12:12.649 --> 12:13.649
(CHAIN CLANKS)

12:14.359 --> 12:15.609
Well, if you decide to buy,

12:15.693 --> 12:17.653
better you than some guru and his cult.

12:17.737 --> 12:18.737
(CHUCKLES)

12:18.822 --> 12:20.155
We could do with some
new blood in the county.

12:21.616 --> 12:23.325
You kids put your safety belts on, now.

12:23.410 --> 12:25.035
Uh, seat belts. Uh...

12:25.745 --> 12:27.496
Okay, folks, take care.

12:28.540 --> 12:31.166
(INDISTINCT TALKING
ON POLICE RADIO)

12:39.008 --> 12:40.426
(INDISTINCT TALKING)

12:40.510 --> 12:41.802
(CHAINSAW BUZZING)

12:55.358 --> 12:58.652
Well, rather than
cherry-pick the odd nice piece,

12:58.736 --> 13:01.405
I'm willing to make
a generous offer of $1 8,500

13:01.489 --> 13:02.781
for the entire contents.

13:02.866 --> 13:05.159
Excuse me, but I'm from
New York, okay?

13:05.243 --> 13:07.035
Go tell your father
I need him down here right now.

13:07.120 --> 13:08.287
Okay.

13:08.371 --> 13:09.872
(SAW WHIRRING)

13:11.040 --> 13:12.291
How much for all these boxes?

13:12.375 --> 13:13.959
Eh, about $5.

13:14.043 --> 13:15.043
Dad...

13:15.128 --> 13:16.837
COOPER: It's a beautiful
house, it's a beautiful town.

13:16.921 --> 13:18.005
-Dad.
-Yeah?

13:18.089 --> 13:19.131
Mom needs you.

13:19.215 --> 13:20.466
Uh, in a minute, Jesse.

13:20.550 --> 13:21.884
Okay, she said she needed you now.

13:21.968 --> 13:24.344
I know, I know,
but I'm busy right now, okay?

13:24.429 --> 13:26.638
Stan, Declan, this way. Come on.

13:27.891 --> 13:29.099
All right.

13:29.184 --> 13:31.310
Stan, put that box right up there.

13:31.394 --> 13:33.645
Declan, take that box into the office.

14:20.944 --> 14:22.110
"Grady"?

14:29.619 --> 14:30.744
All this goes, too?

14:30.828 --> 14:32.454
Uh, yeah.

14:33.748 --> 14:34.831
I think so.

14:34.916 --> 14:36.124
What about this room?

14:37.001 --> 14:38.252
Oh, God, there's so many
rooms in this house.

14:38.378 --> 14:39.628
(CHUCKLES) I know.

14:42.924 --> 14:43.924
Oh, boy.

14:44.008 --> 14:45.092
Maps.

14:45.510 --> 14:46.718
Paper work.

14:47.845 --> 14:49.346
Maps and more maps.

14:50.557 --> 14:51.640
(THUMP)

15:29.804 --> 15:32.097
"Hammerhand will find the weak.

15:32.932 --> 15:35.309
"Hurl them down to rot and reek.

15:36.144 --> 15:38.270
"Bash your skull and toss you in.

15:39.314 --> 15:42.858
"Your pain is short.
Your blood runs thin.

15:43.901 --> 15:46.737
"The strong are spared
to breed and spawn.

15:48.531 --> 15:51.074
<i>"Graze around the devil's yawn."</i>

16:31.532 --> 16:32.616
What are you doing?

16:32.700 --> 16:35.077
Um, just going over all these papers.

16:37.288 --> 16:39.081
The kids are starving.
Do you want to go eat?

16:39.165 --> 16:40.624
Yeah, I'm hungry.

16:40.708 --> 16:42.501
-Yeah, me, too.
-Look at this.

16:42.585 --> 16:43.877
-Is that this house?
-Yes.

16:43.961 --> 16:45.504
-Look at that.
-Wow.

16:45.588 --> 16:48.048
That was taken
in the '30s. Look at that car.

16:48.132 --> 16:49.508
(BOTH LAUGHING)

16:50.301 --> 16:52.260
Isn't it great? Look at the yard.

16:52.679 --> 16:54.179
(CHUCKLING)
Doesn't look like that now.

16:54.263 --> 16:55.722
No. But it will again.

16:55.807 --> 16:56.932
Think so?

16:57.016 --> 16:58.016
After you mow it.

16:58.101 --> 16:59.267
(LAUGHS)

17:01.938 --> 17:03.438
Let's go eat. I'm hungry.

17:04.107 --> 17:05.272
Okay.

17:05.650 --> 17:06.817
(CHUCKLES)

17:40.268 --> 17:41.309
LEAH: Kristen...

17:41.644 --> 17:43.186
Would you mind
hanging up the phone...

17:43.271 --> 17:44.271
Where'd you get that jacket?

17:44.355 --> 17:46.106
...and joining
the rest of us for dinner, please?

17:46.190 --> 17:47.524
-It's Grady's.
-All right, then...

17:47.608 --> 17:48.775
Hot drinks. Who had the tea?

17:48.860 --> 17:50.235
-COOPER: Oh, she had the tea.
-You had the tea?

17:50.319 --> 17:51.903
-LEAH: Yeah.
-Tea for you.

17:51.988 --> 17:54.406
And coffee for you.
And cream and sugar?

17:54.490 --> 17:55.615
-I'll take some cream.
-Cream.

17:55.742 --> 17:58.076
How do they have any right
to be dumping his stuff?

17:58.161 --> 18:00.287
They bought it.
They bought everything in it.

18:00.371 --> 18:02.414
So? They could rent a locker.

18:02.498 --> 18:03.999
They could put it in storage.

18:04.375 --> 18:06.042
(INDISTINCT TALKING)

18:06.878 --> 18:07.961
And the cream.

18:08.045 --> 18:09.087
-COOPER: Oh, thanks.
-Great.

18:09.172 --> 18:10.255
Everything's, uh... Food's okay?

18:10.339 --> 18:11.465
-Yeah, good. Yeah.
-Everything's good?

18:11.674 --> 18:13.633
(CHUCKLES)
Hey, I'm Cooper, by the way.

18:13.801 --> 18:15.051
Ah. Ray Pinski.

18:15.136 --> 18:16.261
-How are you?
-Great to meet you.

18:16.345 --> 18:17.679
-This is Leah. Kristen.
-Leah. Hi.

18:17.764 --> 18:18.930
Jesse.

18:19.515 --> 18:21.141
-Uh, Jesse? (LAUGH)
-Yeah.

18:21.225 --> 18:22.434
-Kristen.
-Ray...

18:22.518 --> 18:24.186
-Ray?
-Oh, uh, my wife.

18:24.520 --> 18:26.438
I'm Ellen Pinski. Hi.

18:26.522 --> 18:28.106
This is our daughter, Stephanie.

18:28.191 --> 18:29.274
Hi.

18:29.609 --> 18:31.234
-Hi. Leah.
-Hi.

18:31.861 --> 18:33.653
Do you, uh... Do you kids like horses?

18:33.738 --> 18:34.905
Mom...

18:35.198 --> 18:36.865
-COOPER: Oh, yeah.
-Oh, yeah. Sure.

18:37.325 --> 18:39.284
Well, Stephanie has a horse,

18:39.368 --> 18:41.036
and I think he needs feeding right now.

18:41.871 --> 18:42.954
Would that be okay?

18:43.039 --> 18:44.247
-Oh. Yeah, sure. Hey. Hey.
-Oh, yeah.

18:44.332 --> 18:45.832
-Cool.
-COOPER: Want to go?

18:45.917 --> 18:47.626
LEAH:
Kristen, why don't you go, too?

18:47.710 --> 18:50.378
Hmm? Go on. Go.

18:50.797 --> 18:52.255
I said... I said, "Go."

18:52.340 --> 18:53.590
Go. Now.

18:53.716 --> 18:55.967
And why don't you
leave that cell phone here with me?

18:56.052 --> 18:58.929
Then if someone calls,
I can tell 'em where you are.

19:02.183 --> 19:03.308
They're at that age.

19:03.392 --> 19:04.726
COOPER: (SIGHS)
She's tough.

19:04.811 --> 19:05.936
LEAH: (CHUCKLING) Yeah.

19:06.020 --> 19:07.521
Kids love horses, though. I mean...

19:07.605 --> 19:09.648
Well, basically, she loves cell phones,

19:09.732 --> 19:11.900
but I'm hoping she'll
move into horses eventually.

19:12.568 --> 19:13.735
(LAUGHS)

19:13.945 --> 19:15.070
(LAUGHS)

